{"author":{"id":"30a9cdd9e5369167dc36be4d3e5f98e516aa30b7571a17013bc815eef45f09c3"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1643196446,"nonce":"ikh46YkDV18JxF2ygKaoc3V14WU=","metadata":{"github-id":"I_kwDOAW4Y0s5CdDwQ","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/4349","origin":"github"},"title":"Replace reviewer guide with automation.","message":"Half the things on this list could be checked automatically: https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/blob/master/docs/guide_for_reviewers.md\n\nI think this would make a good paper-cut, these checks can be written easily and incrementally and added as needed.\n\nHere are some examples of things that can be checked automatically:\n\n- [ ] Is there a .shed.yml file?\n- [ ] Is there a tool .xml file?\n- [ ] No tool_dependencies.xml file. (Has been deprecated and is no longer \"Best Practice\")\n- [ ]  Is there a correctly-formatted .shed.yml file?\n- [ ]  Does the name match the folder name and, in the case of a single tool, the tool .xml file name? Alphanumeric and underscore _ only, no - (and apparently not `.`)\n- [ ]  Is there a description? Are there homepage_url and remote_repository_url fields?\n- [ ] Does the tool pass planemo/travis lint with no warnings or errors?\n- [ ] 4 spaces indentation?\n- [ ] Are the XML elements in the order suggested in the Best Practices Coding Style?\n- [ ]  Are the id and name ~sensible and~ not previously used? - I don't even know how you'd check this. Is there a TS api for this?\n- [ ]  Does the version follow PEP 440 with +galaxyN?\n- [ ] Is there a @TOOL_VERSION@ macro token used\n- [ ] Is there a description tag?\n- [ ] Is the description of suitable length?\n- [ ]  If there is more than one tool present (tool collection), is there a macros.xml file?\n- [ ] Is there a \u003cstdio /\u003e element, or does \u003ccommand /\u003e have a detect_errors attribute, or does the tool specify a profile attribute?\n- [ ] Is there a version command?\n- [ ] Is it book-ended with \u003c![CDATA[ ... ]]\u003e tags?\n\nand so on, the fast majority of things on the list can be checked automatically and guidance provided in the form of either suggestions or comments directly on the code by a bot, saving reviewers a lot of time and an absolutely too-long checklist for reviewing tools which is a high burden for reviewers and might make it easier to merge things more freely.","files":null}]}